	volume = {7},
	issn = {0015-749X},
	abstract = {Measurements of several hundred open-grown (a) Oak and Hickory and (b) Norway Spruce showed high correlations (r = 0.983 and 0.991 respectively) between crown width (CW) and d.b.h. (D), independent of age or site. The \% of an acre covered by the crown of an open-grown tree is regarded as the maximum crown area (MCA) e.g. open-grown Spruce of 16 in. D have a mean CW of 26 ft., a crown area of 531 sq. ft. and a MCA of 1.22\%. The sum of the MCA's of a stand divided by its area is the crown competition factor (CCF) which is derivable from a stand table and CW/D regression equations, which for (a) above are CW = 1.829 D + 3.12, and for (b) CW = 1.313 D + 5.057. The general MCA value is pi (CW)2/ 4/435.6 = 0.0018 (CW)2. For Norway Spruce-squaring CW values of (b)-the MCA is 0.0031 D2 + 0.0239 D + 0-0460. In pure Oak stands, a consistent ceiling density with a CCF of 200 was found; a consistent ceiling probably exists for all species. Applications to a stand table of Oak, tests against data for Oaks and Sitka Spruce, and comparisons with other density criteria are discussed. Theoretically the method is applicable to uneven-aged stands. Site and stand age appear definitely not to influence CCF. [Cf. F.A. 18 No. 3222. KEYWORDS: Carya crown size {\textbackslash} Crown crown diam./d.b.h. {\textbackslash} Mensuration forest {\textbackslash} Picea abies crown competition {\textbackslash} Picea abies stand density {\textbackslash} Quercus crown competition {\textbackslash} Quercus stand density},
